\r (Gen. 5:1-32; 10:1-32; 11:10-26)
\rem /s2 To Noah's Sons
\p
\v 1 Adam, Shet \add (SethÂŠ187052)\add*, EnoshÂŠ187053,
\v 2 Kenan, MahalalelÂŠ187056, YaredÂŠ187057 \add (Jared)\add*,
\v 3 Hanok \add (Enoch)\add*, Metushelah \add (MethuselahÂŠ187060)\add*, LamekÂŠ187061,
\v 4 Noah, ShemÂŠ187064, HamÂŠ187065, andÂŠ187066 YafetÂŠ187066 \add (Japeth)\add*.
\rem /s1 Descendants of Japheth
\rem /s2 The Japhethites
\p
\v 5 Yafet's sonsÂŠ187069 were GomerÂŠ187071, MagogÂŠ187072, MadayÂŠ187073, YavanÂŠ187074, Tuval, MeshekÂŠ187076, and TirasÂŠ187077.
\v 6 Gomer'sÂŠ187081 sonsÂŠ187080 were AshkenazÂŠ187082, RifatÂŠ187083, and TogarmahÂŠ187084.
\v 7 Yavan'sÂŠ187087 sonsÂŠ187086 were ElishahÂŠ187088, TarshishÂŠ187089, KittimÂŠ187090, andÂŠ187086 RodanimÂŠ187091.
\rem /s1 Descendants of Ham
\rem /s2 The Hamites
\p
\v 8 Ham'sÂŠ187095 sonsÂŠ187094 were Kush, Mitsrayim, PutÂŠ187098, and KanaanÂŠ187099.
\v 9 Kush's sons were SebaÂŠ187103, HavilahÂŠ187104, SabtaÂŠ187105, Raamah, and Savteka. Raamah'sÂŠ187109 sons were Sheva and DedanÂŠ187111.
\v 10 Then KushÂŠ187114 fatheredÂŠ187115 NimrodÂŠ187118 \add and\add* he became a mightyÂŠ187122 \add warrior\add*.
\v 11 Mitsrayim was the ancestor of the Lud, the AnamÂŠ187134, the LehabÂŠ187137, the NaftuhÂŠ187140,
\v 12 the PatrusÂŠ187144, the Kasluh, andÂŠ187142 the KaftorÂŠ187154 people groups. (The PhilistinesÂŠ187151 descended from the Kasluh people group.)
\v 13 Kanaan'sÂŠ187157 firstÂŠ187162 son was Tsidon, and then \add âheÂŠ187158 was also the ancestor of the Hittites\add*,
\v 14 the YebusitesÂŠ187169, the AmoritesÂŠ187172, the GirgashitesÂŠ187174,
\v 15 the HivitesÂŠ187178, the ArkitesÂŠ187181, the SinitesÂŠ187184,
\v 16 the ArvaditesÂŠ187188, the ZemaritesÂŠ187191, andÂŠ187186 the HamatitesÂŠ187194.
\rem /s1 Descendants of Shem
\rem /s2 The Semites
\p
\v 17 Shem'sÂŠ187198 sons were ElamÂŠ187199, Ashur, ArpakshadÂŠ187201, LudÂŠ187202, and Aram. \add Aram'sÂŠ187203 sons were\add*: Uts, HulÂŠ187205, GeterÂŠ187206, and MeshekÂŠ187207.
\v 18 ArpakshadÂŠ187210 was the father of Shelah, and Shelah was the father of EberÂŠ187219.
\v 19 Eber had twoÂŠ187223 sonsÂŠ187224: PelegÂŠ187227 (\add which sounds like the Hebrew word for âdividedâ\add*, because in his lifetime, the earthÂŠ187231 was divided)\x + \xo 1:19 \xt Gen 11:1-9.\x* andÂŠ187221 YoktanÂŠ187234.
\v 20 Yoktan was the ancestor of: AlmodadÂŠ187240, ShelefÂŠ187243, Hatsarmavet, YerahÂŠ187249,
\v 21 HadoramÂŠ187253, UzalÂŠ187256, DiklahÂŠ187259,
\v 22 Eybal, AbimaelÂŠ187266, Sheva,
\v 23 OfirÂŠ187273, HavilahÂŠ187276, andÂŠ187271 Yovav. All those were the descendants of YoktanÂŠ187284.
\p
\v 24 \add These were the descendants of\add* ShemÂŠ187287 \add (in order from him to Abraham)\add*: Arpakshad, ShelahÂŠ187290,
\v 25 Eber, PelegÂŠ187293, ReuÂŠ187294,
\v 26 Serug, NahorÂŠ187297, TerahÂŠ187298,
\v 27 and Abram (\add whose name God later changed to\add* AbrahamÂŠ187302).
\s1 Yishmael's descendants
\rem /s1 Descendants of Abraham; From Abraham to Jacob; The Family of Abraham; The Descendants of Ishmael
\r (Gen. 25:12-16)
\p
\v 28 Abraham'sÂŠ187306 sonsÂŠ187305 were Yitshak \add (IsaacÂŠ187307)\add* andÂŠ187308 YishmaelÂŠ187308 \add (Ishmael)\add*.
\rem /s2 Descendants of Hagar
\v 29 These were theirÂŠ187312 family lines: The firstÂŠ187313 son born to YishmaelÂŠ187314 \add (the son of Abraham's slave-wife Hagar)\add* was Nevayot, then his other sons KedarÂŠ187316, AdbeelÂŠ187317, MibsamÂŠ187318,
\v 30 MishmaÂŠ187320, DumahÂŠ187321, MassaÂŠ187322, HadadÂŠ187323, TemaÂŠ187324,
\v 31 Yetur, NafishÂŠ187327, andÂŠ187328 KedemahÂŠ187328. Those were Yishmael'sÂŠ187332 \add twelve\add* sonsÂŠ187331.
\rem /s2 Descendants of Keturah
\v 32 The sons of Abraham'sÂŠ187338 slave-wife KeturahÂŠ187336 were ZimranÂŠ187342, Yokshan, MedanÂŠ187344, Midyan, YishbakÂŠ187346, and ShuahÂŠ187347. Yokshan'sÂŠ187343 sons were Sheva and DedanÂŠ187351.
\v 33 Midyan's sons were EfahÂŠ187356, EferÂŠ187357, Hanok, AbidaÂŠ187359, and EldaahÂŠ187360. All those were Keturah'sÂŠ187365 descendants.
\rem /s1 The Descendants of Esau; Descendants of Isaac
\rem /s2 Descendants of Sarah
\rem /r (Genesis 36.1-19)
\p
\v 34 AbrahamÂŠ187369 had his son Yitshak \add by his wife Sarah\add*, and Yitshak's sonsÂŠ187374 were EsauÂŠ187376 and \add Yakov, whose name God later changed to\add* YisraelÂŠ187377 \add (IsraelÂŠ187377)\add*.
\s1 Esau's descendants
\rem /s1 Esau's Sons; Descendants of Esau
\r (Gen. 36:1-19)
\p
\v 35 Esau'sÂŠ187381 sonsÂŠ187380 were ElifazÂŠ187382, ReuelÂŠ187383, YeushÂŠ187384, YalamÂŠ187385, and KorahÂŠ187386.
\v 36 Elifaz'sÂŠ187390 sonsÂŠ187389 were TemanÂŠ187391, OmarÂŠ187392, TsefoÂŠ187393, GatamÂŠ187394, KenazÂŠ187395, TimnaÂŠ187396, and AmalekÂŠ187397.
\v 37 Reuel'sÂŠ187401 sonsÂŠ187400 were NahatÂŠ187402, ZerahÂŠ187403, ShammahÂŠ187404, andÂŠ187405 MizzahÂŠ187405.
\s1 Seir's descendants
\rem /s1 Original Peoples of Edom; The Original Inhabitants of Edom
\r (Gen. 36:20-30)
\rem /s2 The People of Seir in Edom
\p
\v 38 SeirÂŠ187409 \add was another descendant of Esau, and his\add* sonsÂŠ187408 were LotanÂŠ187410, ShovalÂŠ187411, Tsiveon, AnahÂŠ187413, DishonÂŠ187414, Etser, and DishanÂŠ187416.
\rem /s1 The Kings of Edom
\rem /r (Genesis 36.31-43)
\v 39 Lotan's sonsÂŠ187418 were HoriÂŠ187420 and HomamÂŠ187421, and Lotan's sisterÂŠ187422 was TimnaÂŠ187424.
\v 40 Shoval's sons were AlyanÂŠ187429, ManahatÂŠ187430, Eyval, ShefoÂŠ187432, and OnamÂŠ187433. Tsiveon's sons were Ayyah and AnahÂŠ187438.
\v 41 Anah'sÂŠ187441 son was Dishon. Dishon'sÂŠ187442 sons were HamranÂŠ187446, EshbanÂŠ187447, IthranÂŠ187448, and KeranÂŠ187449.
\v 42 Etser's sons were BilhanÂŠ187455, ZaavanÂŠ187456, and YaakanÂŠ187457. Dishan's sons were Uts and AranÂŠ187461.
\s1 Edom's rulers
\rem /s1 Rulers of Edom
\r (Gen. 36:31-43)
\rem /s2 The Rulers of Edom
\p
\v 43 These are the kings who ruled the region of EdomÂŠ187469 \add (where Seir's descendants lived)\add* before any kings ruled over YisraelÂŠ187475: BelaÂŠ187476 son of BeorÂŠ187479, and his city's name was Dinhavah.
\v 44 When BelaÂŠ187485 diedÂŠ187484, Zerah'sÂŠ187491 son Yovav from Batsrah \add city\add* \add âreplaced him as king\add*.
\v 45 When Yovav diedÂŠ187494, HushamÂŠ187498 \add âreplaced him as king\add*. He was from the region where the Teman people group lived.
\v 46 When HushamÂŠ187503 diedÂŠ187502, Bedad'sÂŠ187509 son Hadad \add âreplaced him as king\add*. His city's nameÂŠ187516 was AvitÂŠ187518. Hadad defeatedÂŠ187510 the Midyan people group in the MoabÂŠ187515 region.
\v 47 When HadadÂŠ187522 diedÂŠ187521, SamlahÂŠ187525 from MasrekahÂŠ187526 \add city\add* \add âreplaced him as king\add*.
\v 48 WhenÂŠ187533 SamlahÂŠ187529 diedÂŠ187528, ShaulÂŠ187532 from Rehovot-on-the-river \add âreplaced him as king\add*.
\v 49 When ShaulÂŠ187537 diedÂŠ187536, Akbor's son Baal-HananÂŠ187541 \add âreplaced him as king\add*.
\v 50 When Baal-HananÂŠ187548 died, HadadÂŠ187551 \add âreplaced him as king\add*. His city's name was Pa'u. His wife's name was Meheytavelâshe was the daughter of MatredÂŠ187560 \add âandÂŠ187546 the granddaughter\add* of Me-ZahabÂŠ187563.
\p
\v 51 ThenÂŠ187565 HadadÂŠ187566\x + \xo 1:51 \xt 1:46.\x* diedÂŠ187565.
\p The leaders of the EdomÂŠ187570 people group were Chiefs TimnaÂŠ187572, AlvahÂŠ187574, Yetet,
\v 52 AholivamahÂŠ187580, ElahÂŠ187582, PinonÂŠ187584,
\v 53 KenazÂŠ187587, TemanÂŠ187589, MivtsarÂŠ187591,
\v 54 MagdielÂŠ187594, and IramÂŠ187596. Those were the chiefsÂŠ187595 of EdomÂŠ187599.
\c 2
\s1 Yakob's descendants
\rem /s1 The Descendants of Judah; Descendants of Israel; The Sons of Israel and the Descendants of Judah; Israel's Sons
\p
\v 1 These were Yisrael's sonsÂŠ187603: ReuvenÂŠ187605, Shimeon \add (SimeonÂŠ187606)\add*, LeviÂŠ187607, and Yehudah \add (Judah)\add*, Yissakar \add (IssacharÂŠ187609)\add*, and ZebulunÂŠ187610,
\v 2 Dan, YosefÂŠ187613 \add (Joseph)\add*, BenyaminÂŠ187614, NaftaliÂŠ187615, GadÂŠ187616, and AsherÂŠ187617.
\s1 Yehudah's descendants
\rem /s1 Judah; Descendants of Judah
\rem /s2 To Hezron's Sons
\p
\v 3 Yehudah's sons (with the CanaaniteÂŠ187631 woman Bat-Shua) were Er, and OnanÂŠ187623, and ShelahÂŠ187624. (Yehudah's eldest son, Er, was evil in Yahweh's eyesÂŠ187638, and he killed him.)
\v 4 His daughter-in-law TamarÂŠ187643 had \add twin boys named\add* Perets and ZerahÂŠ187652, so altogether YehudahÂŠ187656 had fiveÂŠ187657 sonsÂŠ187655.
\p
\v 5 Perets's sonsÂŠ187660 were Hetsron andÂŠ187664 HamulÂŠ187664.
\v 6 ZerahÂŠ187668 had fiveÂŠ187675 sonsÂŠ187667: ZimriÂŠ187669, Eytan, Heyman, KalkolÂŠ187672, and DaraÂŠ187673.
\v 7 \add Zimri had a son named Karmi.\add* Karmi had a son named Akar who brought troubleÂŠ187681 into YisraelÂŠ187682 \add âby violating a ban\add* on devotedÂŠ187685 thingsÂŠ187685.\x + \xo 2:7: \xt Josh 7:1.\x*
\v 8 Eytan'sÂŠ187689 son was AzaryahÂŠ187690.
\s1 King David's ancestors
\rem /s1 The Family Tree of King David; From Judah's Grandson Hezron to David
\p
\v 9 Hetsron had three sonsÂŠ187692: Yerahme'elÂŠ187700, RamÂŠ187703, andÂŠ187692 Keluvay.\f + \fr 2:9 \ft In the Hebrew, âKeluvayâ is called âKalevâ (Caleb) below.\f*
\rem /s2 From Ram Son of Hezron
\p
\v 10 Ram was the father of Amminadav, andÂŠ187713 Amminadav was the father of NahshonÂŠ187717âa leaderÂŠ187718 of the \add âtribe\add* of YehudahÂŠ187720.
\v 11 Nahshon was the father of Salma. Salma was the father of BoazÂŠ187731.
\v 12 Boaz was the father of Oved. Oved was the father of YishayÂŠ187742 \add (Jesse)\add*.
\v 13 YishayÂŠ187744 had his son EliavÂŠ187751 firstÂŠ187748, AbinadabÂŠ187752 secondÂŠ187753, ShimeaÂŠ187754 thirdÂŠ187755.
\v 14 Netanel fourthÂŠ187758, RaddaiÂŠ187759 fifthÂŠ187760,
\v 15 Otsem sixthÂŠ187763, then DavidÂŠ187764 \add âlast\add*.
\v 16 Their sistersÂŠ187767 were Tseruyah and Avigayil. Tseruyah's threeÂŠ187778 sonsÂŠ187771 were Avshai, Yoav \add (Joab)\add*, and Asah'el.
\v 17 Avigayil had Amasa. Amasa'sÂŠ187784 fatherÂŠ187785 was YeterÂŠ187787, a descendant of YishmaelÂŠ187788 \add (Ishmael)\add*.
\s1 The descendants of Kalev (Caleb)
\rem /s1 The Descendants of Hezron; Descendants of Hezron's Son Caleb
\rem /s2 Caleb Son of Hezron
\p
\v 18 Hetsron's \add third\add* son Kalev \add (Caleb)\add* had sons with Azuvah, one of his wives. The sons were YesherÂŠ187804, Shovav, andÂŠ187790 ArdonÂŠ187806. (The other wife's name was Yeriot.)
\v 19 When Azuvah diedÂŠ187808, Kalev married Efrat, andÂŠ187808 they had a son named HurÂŠ187821.
\v 20 Hur was the father of Uri, andÂŠ187828 Uri was the father of Betsal'el.
\p
\v 21 Later, when Hetsron was sixtyÂŠ187850 years old, he \add âhad sexual intercourse\add* with a daughterÂŠ187840 of MakirÂŠ187842 from the region of GileadÂŠ187844 and marriedÂŠ187846 her. \add @Hetsron's new wife\add* gaveÂŠ187852 birthÂŠ187852 to \add their son\add* Seguv.
\v 22 Seguv was the fatherÂŠ187859 of Yair, andÂŠ187858 Yair controlled twenty-three citiesÂŠ187868 in the GileadÂŠ187870 region.
\v 23 \add âButÂŠ187872\add* GeshurÂŠ187873 and AramÂŠ187875 captured Havvot-YairÂŠ187879 and KenatÂŠ187883 from them, plus \add âtheir surrounding towns\add*âsixtyÂŠ187887 towns \add in all,\add* \add âpopulated by\add* descendants of MakirÂŠ187893 (the fatherÂŠ187894 of GileadÂŠ187896).
\v 24 After Hetsron's deathÂŠ187899 in Kalev-Efratah, his wifeÂŠ187904 Aviyyah gaveÂŠ187907 birthÂŠ187907 to his son AshhurÂŠ187911, the fatherÂŠ187912 of TekoaÂŠ187913.
\s1 Yerahme'el's descendants
\rem /s1 Descendants of Hezron's Son Jerahmeel; The Descendants of Jerahmeel
\rem /s2 Jerahmeel Son of Hezron
\p
\v 25 Hetsron's oldest son was Yerahme'el \add and\add* his sonsÂŠ187916 were RamÂŠ187923 (the oldest), BunahÂŠ187924, OrenÂŠ187925, Otsem, and Ahiyyah.
\v 26 Yerahme'el had anotherÂŠ187931 wifeÂŠ187930 named AtarahÂŠ187934. She was the motherÂŠ187936 of OnamÂŠ187937.
\v 27 The sonsÂŠ187941 of Yerahme'el's oldest son, RamÂŠ187943, were Maats, YaminÂŠ187947, and EkerÂŠ187948.
\v 28 Onam'sÂŠ187953 sons were Shammai and YadaÂŠ187955, and Shammai'sÂŠ187954 sons were Nadav and Avishur.
\p
\v 29 Avishur'sÂŠ187963 wifeÂŠ187962 was AvihayilÂŠ187964, and \add âtheir sons were\add* AhbanÂŠ187969 and MolidÂŠ187972.
\v 30 Nadav's sons were Seled andÂŠ187974 Appayim. (Seled died childless.)
\v 31 Appayim's son was Yishi, Yishi's son was Sheshan, and Sheshan'sÂŠ187989 son was AhlaiÂŠ187992.
\p
\v 32 The sons of Shammai'sÂŠ187997 brotherÂŠ187996 YadaÂŠ187995 were Yeter andÂŠ187994 Yonatan. (Yeter died childless.)
\v 33 Yonatan's sons were PeletÂŠ188008 and ZazaÂŠ188009.
\m Those were the descendants of Yerahme'el.
\p
\v 34 SheshanÂŠ188018 had no sonsÂŠ188019, only daughtersÂŠ188023. He had a \add male\add* servant from Egypt whose nameÂŠ188027 was YarhaÂŠ188028,
\v 35 and SheshanÂŠ188031 gave his daughterÂŠ188034 to \add *him\add* for a wife, and \add âthey had a son\add* AttaiÂŠ188042.
\v 36 Attai was the father of Natan, andÂŠ188049 Natan was the father of Zavad.
\v 37 Zavad was the father of Eflal, andÂŠ188060 Eflal was the father of Oved.
\v 38 Oved was the father of Yehu, andÂŠ188071 Yehu was the father of AzaryahÂŠ188075.
\v 39 Azaryah was the father of Helets, andÂŠ188082 Helets was the father of EleasahÂŠ188086.
\v 40 Eleasah was the father of Sismai, andÂŠ188093 Sismai was the father of ShallumÂŠ188097.
\v 41 ShallumÂŠ188099 was the father of Yekamyah, andÂŠ188104 Yekamyah was the father of Elishama.
\s1 The other descendants of Kalev
\rem /s1 Other Descendants of Caleb; Descendants of Hezron's Son Caleb
\rem /s2 The Clans of Caleb
\p
\v 42 The oldest son of Yerahme'el's brotherÂŠ188112 Kalev was Meysha. Meysha was the father of Zif, andÂŠ188110 Zif was the father of Mareshah. Mareshah was the father of Hevron.
\v 43 Hevron'sÂŠ188126 sonsÂŠ188125 were KorahÂŠ188127, TappuahÂŠ188128, RekemÂŠ188129, andÂŠ188125 ShemaÂŠ188130.
\v 44 ShemaÂŠ188132 was the father of Raham. Raham was the father of YorkeamÂŠ188138. RekemÂŠ188139 was the father of ShammaiÂŠ188143.
\v 45 Shammai'sÂŠ188147 son was Maon, andÂŠ188149 Maon was the fatherÂŠ188150 of Beyt-TsurÂŠ188153.
\v 46 Kalev had a slave-wife named Eyfah who gave birth to Haran, MozaÂŠ188164, andÂŠ188155 Gazez. Haran had a son \add who he also named\add* Gazez.
\v 47 Yahdai'sÂŠ188176 sonsÂŠ188175 were: RegemÂŠ188177, Yotam, GeshanÂŠ188179, PeletÂŠ188180, Eyfah, and ShaaphÂŠ188182.
\p
\v 48 KalevÂŠ188185 had \add another\add* slave-wife named MaacahÂŠ188186 who gave birth to SheberÂŠ188188 andÂŠ188189 TirhanahÂŠ188191.
\v 49 She also gave birthÂŠ188193 to ShaaphÂŠ188194 (the father of MadmannahÂŠ188196), ShevaÂŠ188199 (father of Makbenah and GibeaÂŠ188203), and Kalev's daughterÂŠ188204 Aksah.
\p
\v 50 These people were \add also\add* descendantsÂŠ188212 of Kalev: \add His other wife\add* Efratah had a son Hur. Hur'sÂŠ188216 sons were ShobalÂŠ188219 (\add âfounder\add* of KiriatÂŠ188222-Yearim \add city\add*),
\rem /s1 Descendants of Caleb's Son Hur
\v 51 Salma (\add âfounder\add* of Beyt-Lehem), \add and\add* HarefÂŠ188229 (\add âfounder\add* of Beyt-GaderÂŠ188233).
\v 52 The descendants of ShobalÂŠ188237 (\add âfounder\add* of KiriatÂŠ188240-Yearim) were HaroehÂŠ188241, half of the Manahatites,
\v 53 and the clans from KiriatÂŠ188248-Yearim: the Yitrites, the PutitesÂŠ188250, the ShumatitesÂŠ188251, and the MishraitesÂŠ188252. From those cameÂŠ188254 the Zoratites and EshtaolitesÂŠ188256.
\v 54 Salma'sÂŠ188260 descendants were \add the people of\add* Beyt-Lehem, the Netofatites, the clan of AtrotÂŠ188264-Beyt-Yoav, and half of the Manahatites, \add who were also\add* ZoritesÂŠ188269.
\v 55 The clans of the scribes lived at YabezÂŠ188275: the TiratitesÂŠ188276, the Shimeatites, andÂŠ188271 the SucatitesÂŠ188278. These are the Kenites who descended from HammatÂŠ188282, the ancestor of Rekav's familyÂŠ188271.
\c 3
\s1 King David's children
\rem /s1 Descendants of David; Descendants of David and Solomon; King David's Children
\rem /s2 The Sons of David
\p
\v 1 These were David'sÂŠ188292 sonsÂŠ188291 who were born to him in Hevron: the firstÂŠ188299 was AmnonÂŠ188301 by AhinoamÂŠ188302 the Yezreelite, the secondÂŠ188304 Daniyel by Avigayil the Karmelite,
\v 2 the thirdÂŠ188309 Avishalom \add (AbsalomÂŠ188310)\add*, the son of Maakah (daughterÂŠ188314 of King TalmaiÂŠ188316 of GeshurÂŠ188318), the fourthÂŠ188319 Adoniyyah, the son of HaggitÂŠ188323,
\v 3 the fifthÂŠ188325 Shefatyah by Avital, the sixthÂŠ188328 Yitream by his wife EglahÂŠ188330.
\m
\v 4 Six were born to \add @David\add* in Hevron \add âwhere\add* he reigned for sevenÂŠ188341 and a half years.\x + \xo 3:4: \xt 2Sam 5:4-5; 1Ki 2:11; 1Ch 29:27.\x*
\p Then he reigned in YerushalemÂŠ188349 for thirty-three years
\v 5 and theseÂŠ188352 were born to him \add *there\add*: Beyt-Shua (\add also known as Bathsheba,\add* daughterÂŠ188365 of AmmielÂŠ188367) gave birth to fourÂŠ188361 \add sons\add*: ShimeaÂŠ188357, Shovav, NatanÂŠ188359, and Shelomoh \add (SolomonÂŠ188360)\add*.\x + \xo 3:5: \xt 2Sam 11:3.\x*
\v 6 \add Other sons were\add* Yivhar, Elishama, ElifeletÂŠ188371,
\v 7 NogahÂŠ188373, NefegÂŠ188374, YafiaÂŠ188375,
\v 8 Elishama, Elyada, andÂŠ188377 ElifeletÂŠ188379. (Nine in all.)
\v 9 DavidÂŠ188384 also had sons from his slave-wives. Their sisterÂŠ188390 was TamarÂŠ188389.
\s1 Descendants of King Shelomoh (Solomon)
\rem /s1 The Descendants of King Solomon; Descendants of Solomon
\rem /s2 The Kings of Judah
\p
\v 10 Shelomoh had a son Rehovoam, he had a son Aviyyah, he had a son AsaÂŠ188399, he had a son YehoshafatÂŠ188401,
\v 11 he had a son Yehoram, he had a son AhazyahÂŠ188406, he had a son YoashÂŠ188408,
\v 12 he had a son Amatsyah, he had a son AzaryahÂŠ188413, he had a son YothamÂŠ188415,
\v 13 he had a son Ahaz, he had a son Hizkiyah, he had a son Menashsheh,
\v 14 he had a son Amon, \add and\add* he had a son Yosiyyah.
\v 15 Yosiyyah had four sonsÂŠ188430: The oldest was YohananÂŠ188433, secondÂŠ188434 was Yehoyakim, thirdÂŠ188436 was Tsedekiyyah, \add andÂŠ188430\add* the fourthÂŠ188438 was ShallumÂŠ188439.
\v 16 Yehoyakim had a son Yekaneyah, \add andÂŠ188441\add* he had a son Tsedekiyyah.
\s1 Descendants of King Yekaneyah (Jeconiah)
\rem /s1 Descendants of Jehoiachin; The Descendants of King Jehoiachin
\rem /s2 The Royal Line After the Exile
\p
\v 17 Yekaneyah \add was captured andÂŠ188448 taken to Babylon\add*. His sonsÂŠ188448 were ShealtielÂŠ188451,
\v 18 Malkiram, PedayahÂŠ188455, Shenatstsar, YekamyahÂŠ188457, HoshamaÂŠ188458, andÂŠ188454 Nedavyah.
\v 19 Pedayah'sÂŠ188462 sons were Zerubbavel and ShimeiÂŠ188464. \add Two of\add* Zerubbavel's sons were MeshullamÂŠ188468 and HananyahÂŠ188469, and theirÂŠ188471 sisterÂŠ188471 was ShelomotÂŠ188470.
\v 20 Zerubbavel's fiveÂŠ188479 \add other\add* sons were Hashubah, OhelÂŠ188474, BerekyahÂŠ188475, HasadyahÂŠ188476, andÂŠ188473 Yushab-HesedÂŠ188478.
\v 21 Hananyah'sÂŠ188483 descendants were PelatyahÂŠ188484, YeshayahÂŠ188485, \add and\add* the sons of Refayah, of ArnanÂŠ188489, of Ovadyah, and of Shekanyah.
\v 22 Shekanyah's six descendants were Shemayah and Shemayah'sÂŠ188498 sons HattushÂŠ188501, Yigal, Bariyah, NearyahÂŠ188504, and ShafatÂŠ188505.
\v 23 Nearyah'sÂŠ188510 threeÂŠ188514 sonsÂŠ188508 were Elyoenai, Hizkiyah, andÂŠ188508 AzrikamÂŠ188513.
\v 24 Elyoenai's sevenÂŠ188526 sonsÂŠ188516 were HodavyahÂŠ188518, Eliashiv, PelayahÂŠ188521, Akkuv, YohananÂŠ188523, DelayahÂŠ188524, andÂŠ188516 AnaniÂŠ188525.
\c 4
\s1 The other descendants of Yehudah (Judah)
\rem /s1 The Descendants of Judah; Descendants of Judah; Other Descendants of Judah
\rem /s2 Other Clans of Judah
\p
\v 1 Yehudah'sÂŠ188530 sonsÂŠ188529 were Perets, Hetsron, Karmi, HurÂŠ188534, and Shoval.
\v 2 Shoval had a son Reayah, Reayah had a son Yahat, and Yahat had AhumaiÂŠ188549 and LahadÂŠ188552. Those were the ancestors of the Tsoratites.
\v 3 Yezreel, IshmaÂŠ188562, and IdbashÂŠ188563 \add âstarted the clans that lived in\add* Eytam \add city\add*, and they had a sisterÂŠ188565 named Hatselelponi.
\v 4 Hur was the firstÂŠ188578 son born to \add his mother\add* Efratah, \add and\add* he \add âfounded\add* Beyt-Lehem \add city\add*. Hur had theseÂŠ188574 descendantsÂŠ188575: Penuel and Ezer. Penuel \add âstarted the clans that lived in\add* GedorÂŠ188570 \add city\add*, and Ezer \add âstarted the clans that lived in\add* HushahÂŠ188573 \add city\add*.
\v 5 \add Hetsron's son\add* AshhurÂŠ188584, the fatherÂŠ188585 of TekoaÂŠ188586, had twoÂŠ188588 wivesÂŠ188589, HelahÂŠ188590 andÂŠ188591 NaarahÂŠ188591,
\v 6 and NaarahÂŠ188595 bore him AhuzzamÂŠ188598, HeferÂŠ188601, Teymeni, and HaahashtariÂŠ188607.
\v 7 \add Ashhur andÂŠ188617 his wife\add* Helah'sÂŠ188613 sonsÂŠ188612 were TseretÂŠ188614, Tsohar, EtnanÂŠ188617,
\v 8 and Kots. Kots was the fatherÂŠ188620 of AnubÂŠ188623 and Hatstsovevah, and the ancestor of the clans descended from Harum'sÂŠ188631 son AharhelÂŠ188628.
\p
\v 9 Yabets was more respected than his brothersÂŠ188636. His motherÂŠ188637 had named him Yabets \add (which sounds like the word meaning âpainâ)\add*, saying, âIt's because I bore him in pain.â
\v 10 Yabets calledÂŠ188646 out to Yisrael's god, saying, âOh, please give me a real blessing, and \add âhelp me\add* and enlargeÂŠ188655 my territory, and don'tÂŠ188664 \add âdo anything to harm me\add*, so thatÂŠ188669 I won'tÂŠ188664 be in pain.â And GodÂŠ188648 \add âdid what Yabets requested\add*.
\rem /s1 Other Family Lists
\p
\v 11 \add Another of Yehudah's descendants was\add* ShuhahÂŠ188676. His brotherÂŠ188674 Kelub was the father of Mehir. Mehir was the father of EshtonÂŠ188683.
\v 12 Eshton was the fatherÂŠ188697 of Beyt-RafaÂŠ188690, PaseahÂŠ188693, andÂŠ188685 Tehinnah. Tehinnah \add ?âfounded\add* NahashÂŠ188699 city, but \add âlived in\add* RekahÂŠ188702.
\p
\v 13 Kenaz'sÂŠ188706 sons were Otniel and SerayahÂŠ188708. And Otniel'sÂŠ188707 sons were HathathÂŠ188711 \add ?and Meonotai\add*.\f + \fr 4:13 \ft Not in the Hebrew, but âsonsâ was plural, so it seems that it may have been accidentally dropped out of the text.\f*
\v 14 Meonotai had a son OfrahÂŠ188717, andÂŠ188718 SerayahÂŠ188718 fatheredÂŠ188723 Yoav, the \add âfounder\add* of Craftsmen's Valley, because theyÂŠ188728 were craftsmenÂŠ188727.
\p
\v 15 The sons of Kalev (Yefunneh'sÂŠ188735 son) were Iru, Elah, and NaamÂŠ188738, and Elah'sÂŠ188737 son was KenazÂŠ188741.
\p
\v 16 Yehallelel'sÂŠ188744 sonsÂŠ188743 were ZifÂŠ188745, ZifahÂŠ188746, TiriyaÂŠ188747, andÂŠ188743 AsarelÂŠ188748.
\p
\v 17 Ezrah'sÂŠ188752 sonsÂŠ188750 were YeterÂŠ188753, Mered, EferÂŠ188755, and YalonÂŠ188756. And \add ?@Mered's wife Bityah\add* conceivedÂŠ188757 Miryam, ShammaiÂŠ188763, and IshbahÂŠ188766, the fatherÂŠ188767 of EshtemoaÂŠ188768.
\v 18 \add *She\add* was one of Far-oh's \add (Pharaoh'sÂŠ188793)\add* daughtersÂŠ188791. Mered'sÂŠ188796 wife, who was a descendant of Yehudah \add (Judah)\add*, gave birth to YeredÂŠ188775 the father of GedorÂŠ188777, Hever the father of Sokoh, andÂŠ188770 Yekutiel the father of ZanoahÂŠ188787.
\v 19 The sons of Hodiyyah's wife (Naham'sÂŠ188803 sisterÂŠ188802) were the father of KeilahÂŠ188805 the GarmiteÂŠ188806 and \add âĄthe father of\add* EshtemoaÂŠ188807 the Maakatite.
\p
\v 20 Shimon'sÂŠ188811 sons were AmnonÂŠ188812, RinnahÂŠ188813, Ben-HananÂŠ188816, and TilonÂŠ188817.
\rem /s1 The Descendants of Shelah; Descendants of Judah's Son Shelah
\p Ishi'sÂŠ188820 sons were Zohet and Ben-Zohet.
\s1 Shelah's descendants
\p
\v 21 The sons of ShelahÂŠ188827 (one of Yehudah'sÂŠ188830 sons) were ErÂŠ188831 (father of Lekah), LaadahÂŠ188834 (father of MareshahÂŠ188836 and the clans \add âwho worked with\add* linenÂŠ188841 at Beyt-AshbeaÂŠ188843),
\v 22 Yokim and the menÂŠ188846 of KozebaÂŠ188847, and YoashÂŠ188848 and SarafÂŠ188849, who ruledÂŠ188852 in Moav and Yashubi-LehemÂŠ188854. (\add âAll this is from ancientÂŠ188857 recordsÂŠ188856\add*.)
\v 23 They were the pottersÂŠ188860 \add âwho lived in\add* NetaimÂŠ188862 and GederahÂŠ188863âtheyÂŠ188868 lived thereÂŠ188869 and \add âworked for\add* the kingÂŠ188866.
\s1 The descendants of Shimeon (Simeon)
\rem /s1 The Descendants of Simeon; Descendants of Simeon; Simeon
\p
\v 24 Shimeon'sÂŠ188873 sons were NemuelÂŠ188874, YaminÂŠ188875, YaribÂŠ188876, ZerahÂŠ188877, andÂŠ188875 ShaulÂŠ188878.
\v 25 Shaul's son was Shallum. Shallum's son was Mivsam. Mivsam's son was MishmaÂŠ188884.
\v 26 The \add following were\add* Mishma's descendants: Mishma's son was Hammuel. Hammuel'sÂŠ188889 son was Zakkur. Zakkur's son was ShimeiÂŠ188893.
\v 27 Shimei had sixteen sons andÂŠ188896 six daughtersÂŠ188900, but none of his brothersÂŠ188902 had many children, so Shimeon's \add âdescendantsÂŠ188912 were never as numerous as those\add* of \add his younger brother\add* YehudahÂŠ188913 \add (Judah)\add*.
\p
\v 28 \add @Shimeon's descendants\add* livedÂŠ188916 in \add these cities and towns\add*: Be'er-Sheva \add (Beersheba)\add*, MoladahÂŠ188920, Hatsar-Shual,\x + \xo 4:28-33: \xt Josh 19:2-8.\x*
\v 29 Bilhah, Etsem, Tolad,
\v 30 Betuel, HormahÂŠ188929, TsiklagÂŠ188930,
\v 31 Beyt-Markaboth, Hatsar-Susim, Beyt-Biri, andÂŠ188932 ShaaraimÂŠ188938. \add âThey lived in those places untilÂŠ188941 DavidÂŠ188944 became king\add*.
\v 32 They \add also\add* lived in fiveÂŠ188953 villagesÂŠ188946: Eytam, Ayin, RimmonÂŠ188949, TokenÂŠ188950, andÂŠ188946 AshanÂŠ188951,
\v 33 and all the villagesÂŠ188957 aroundÂŠ188959 theseÂŠ188961 towns as far as BaalÂŠ188964. Those were their settlementsÂŠ188966, and theyÂŠ188967 keptÂŠ188967 their genealogicalÂŠ188967 recordsÂŠ188967.
\p
\v 34 \add Their clan leaders were\add* Meshovav, Yamlek, YoshahÂŠ188972 the son of Amatsyah,
\v 35 Yoel, YehuÂŠ188978 the son of YoshibiahÂŠ188981, the son of SerayahÂŠ188984, the son of AsielÂŠ188987,
\v 36 as well as Elioenai, YaakobahÂŠ188990, YeshohaiahÂŠ188991, AsayahÂŠ188992, AdielÂŠ188993, YesimielÂŠ188994, BenayahÂŠ188995,
\v 37 andÂŠ188997 Ziza the son of ShifiÂŠ189000, the son of AllonÂŠ189003, the son of YedayahÂŠ189006, the son of ShimriÂŠ189009, the son of ShemayahÂŠ189012.
\v 38 Those who are named above were the leadersÂŠ189017 of their clans, and their \add extended\add* familiesÂŠ189018 increased greatlyÂŠ189022 in number,
\v 39 andÂŠ189024 they wentÂŠ189024 to the entranceÂŠ189025 of GedorÂŠ189026 (to the east of the valleyÂŠ189029) in search of pastureÂŠ189031 for theirÂŠ189032 flocksÂŠ189032.
\v 40 They foundÂŠ189034 goodÂŠ189037, \add âfertileÂŠ189036\add* pastureÂŠ189035, and the land was \add âwide\add*, and quietÂŠ189041 and peacefulÂŠ189042, because Ham'sÂŠ189046 \add âdescendants\add* had livedÂŠ189047 thereÂŠ189048 \add âpreviously\add*.
\p
\v 41 Those listed by nameÂŠ189054 wentÂŠ189051 \add there\add* in the daysÂŠ189055 of Yehudah'sÂŠ189060 King HizkiyahÂŠ189057 and struck down the tentsÂŠ189064 of the MeunitesÂŠ189067 who were foundÂŠ189070 there. They completely annihilated them (to this dayÂŠ189076), and they livedÂŠ189078 \add there\add* in their placeÂŠ189079 because there was pastureÂŠ189082 for their flocksÂŠ189083 there.
\v 42 ThenÂŠ189086 fiveÂŠ189096 hundredÂŠ189097 of theirÂŠ189104 menÂŠ189095 who were descendantsÂŠ189090 of Shimeon wentÂŠ189092 to Mt. SeirÂŠ189094, \add âled\add* by Yishi's sonsÂŠ189102 PelatyahÂŠ189098, NearyahÂŠ189099, Refayah, andÂŠ189086 UzzielÂŠ189101.
\v 43 They \add also\add* struck down the rest of the AmalekitesÂŠ189111 who escapedÂŠ189110, andÂŠ189112 they've livedÂŠ189112 thereÂŠ189113 to this dayÂŠ189115.
\c 5
\s1 Reuven's descendants
\rem /s1 Reuben; Descendants of Reuben; The Descendants of Reuben
\p
\v 1 Reuven was the first \add child\add* born to Yisrael \add (or IsraelÂŠ189122, also known as Yakov/Jacob)\add*, but when he \add âhad sex with one of his father'sÂŠ189128 slave-wives\add*, his birthright was givenÂŠ189129 to the sons of YosefÂŠ189132 \add (Joseph)\add*, \add âanother one of Yisrael's sons\add*. \add âSoÂŠ189118 Reuven wasn't recorded as inheriting\add* the birthright,\x + \xo 5:1: \xt Gen 35:22; 49:3-4; Gen 49:8-10.\x*
\v 2 \add âand although\add* YehudahÂŠ189141 \add (Judah)\add* was strongerÂŠ189142 than his \add other\add* brothersÂŠ189143 and \add âwould be the son to produce a rulerÂŠ189144\add*, the birthrightÂŠ189146 went to Yosef.
\v 3 The sonsÂŠ189150 of Yisrael's eldest son Reuven were Hanok, PalluÂŠ189155, Hetsron, and Karmi.
\p
\v 4 \add Another of Reuven's descendantsÂŠ189159 was\add* YoelÂŠ189160, and his son was Shemayah. Shemayah'sÂŠ189161 son was Gog. Gog'sÂŠ189163 son was ShimeiÂŠ189165.\x + \xo 5:6: \xt 2Ki 15:29.\x*
\v 5 Shimei's son was Mikah. Mikah's son was Reayah. Reayah'sÂŠ189170 son was BaalÂŠ189172.
\v 6 Baal's son was Beerah, who became a leaderÂŠ189184 of the Reuvenites, \add but\add* the Assyrian King TiglatÂŠ189179-Pileser \add âcaptured him and tookÂŠ189178 him back to AssyriaÂŠ189182\add*.
\v 7 His brothers by their clans, \add âas listed in their genealogicalÂŠ189189 records\add*: YeielÂŠ189192 the leader, Zekaryah,
\v 8 Bela son of AzazÂŠ189198, son of ShemaÂŠ189201, son of YoelÂŠ189204. Reuven's clan lived near the city of AroerÂŠ189207 \add as far north as the cities of\add* Nevo andÂŠ189195 Baal-Meon.
\v 9 \add Some of them lived further\add* east, as far as the edge of the desert that extends to the EuphratesÂŠ189224 River, because theirÂŠ189226 livestockÂŠ189226 had multiplied \add back\add* in the GileadÂŠ189229 region.
\v 10 (In the daysÂŠ189231 of \add King\add* ShaulÂŠ189232, they'd battled with the HagritesÂŠ189237 andÂŠ189231 \add âdefeated them, so thenÂŠ189231\add* they'd livedÂŠ189240 in their tentsÂŠ189241 all over \add âeasternÂŠ189247\add* GileadÂŠ189248.)
\s1 Gad's descendants
\rem /s1 Descendants of Gad; The Descendants of Gad; Gad
\p
\v 11 Gad'sÂŠ189253 descendants lived opposite them in the BashanÂŠ189257 region as far as SalkahÂŠ189260:
\v 12 Yoel was their leader, ShafamÂŠ189264 was second-in-command, others were YanaiÂŠ189266 and ShafatÂŠ189267 in BashanÂŠ189268.
\v 13 \add âTheir cousins who were leaders of sevenÂŠ189280 clans were\add* Mikael, MeshullamÂŠ189274, Sheva, YoraiÂŠ189276, Yakan, ZiaÂŠ189278, andÂŠ189270 EberÂŠ189279.
\v 14 Those were descendants of Avihayil, the son of HuriÂŠ189289, the son of YaroahÂŠ189292, the son of GileadÂŠ189295, the son of Mikael, the son of YeshishaiÂŠ189301, the son of YahdoÂŠ189304, the son of BuzÂŠ189307.
\v 15 Ahi was the son of Avdiel, the son of GuniÂŠ189315, head of theirÂŠ189318 clans.
\v 16 \add @Those descendants of Gad\add* livedÂŠ189320 in \add âtownsÂŠ189323\add* in the GileadÂŠ189321 and BashanÂŠ189322 regions, and on all the pasturelandÂŠ189326 \add âthroughout the SharonÂŠ189327 Plain\add*.
\v 17 All of them were listed in the genealogies in the days of Yehudah'sÂŠ189338 King YothamÂŠ189335 and Yisrael's King YeroboamÂŠ189340.
\s1 The eastern warriors
\rem /s1 The Tribes East of the Jordan; The Armies of the Eastern Tribes
\p
\v 18 There were 44,760 warriors descendedÂŠ189346 from strong menÂŠ189359 in the tribes of ReuvenÂŠ189348 and Gad and the \add eastern\add* half of the tribe of MenashshehÂŠ189353. They all carriedÂŠ189360 shieldsÂŠ189361 and swordsÂŠ189362, and bows and arrows, and were all trained to fight in battles.
\v 19 They went to war against the HagritesÂŠ189381, YeturÂŠ189382, NafishÂŠ189383, andÂŠ189377 Nodav,
\v 20 and were helpedÂŠ189386 because they called out to God in the battleÂŠ189396. \add âSoÂŠ189386\add* with God answeringÂŠ189397 their prayersÂŠ189397 because of their trustÂŠ189401 in him, they \add âwere able to defeat\add* the HagritesÂŠ189390 and their \add âallies\add*.
\v 21 They capturedÂŠ189404 their livestockÂŠ189405, including 50,000 camelsÂŠ189406, 250,000 sheepÂŠ189409, andÂŠ189404 2,000 donkeysÂŠ189413, as well as 100,000 people,
\v 22 because many were killed \add âas a result of God's assistance\add*. Then they livedÂŠ189428 in that \add âarea\add* untilÂŠ189430 the exileÂŠ189432.
\s1 Menashsheh's descendants
\rem /s1 The Half-Tribe of Manasseh; The People of East Manasseh
\p
\v 23 The descendants of the half tribeÂŠ189437 of MenashshehÂŠ189438 lived in the BashanÂŠ189441 region as far as BaalÂŠ189444-Hermon and SenirÂŠ189446, and Mt. Hermon, \add and\add* they \add âincreased in number\add*.
\v 24 Their clan leaders were EferÂŠ189458, Yishi, ElielÂŠ189460, AzrielÂŠ189461, Yermiyah, HodavyahÂŠ189463, and YahdielÂŠ189464. They were all powerful and famous warriors, and leaders of their clans.
\s1 The exile of the eastern tribes
\rem /s1 The Eastern Tribes Are Deported
\p
\v 25 \add âButÂŠ189474\add* they disobeyed theirÂŠ189476 ancestors'ÂŠ189476 god, andÂŠ189474 they prostitutedÂŠ189477 themselves to the godsÂŠ189479 of the peoplesÂŠ189480 that GodÂŠ189475 had destroyedÂŠ189485 \add âahead of them\add* in that region.
\v 26 \add âSoÂŠ189489\add* Yisrael'sÂŠ189491 godÂŠ189490 stirredÂŠ189489 up the spirit of the Assyrian King PulÂŠ189496 (\add âalso known as\add* TilgathÂŠ189503-Pileser). He took them into exileâthat is, the Reuvenites, the GaditesÂŠ189509, and the half tribeÂŠ189511 of MenashshehÂŠ189512. ThenÂŠ189489 he took them to HalahÂŠ189514, HaborÂŠ189515, HaraÂŠ189516, and the riverÂŠ189517 of GozanÂŠ189518 (\add where they still are\add* toÂŠ189519 this dayÂŠ189520).\x + \xo 5:26: a \xt 2Ki 15:19; \xo b \xt 2Ki 15:29; \xo c \xt 2Ki 17:6.\x*
\c 6
\s1 Levi's descendants
\rem /s1 Descendants of Levi; The Priestly Line; The Family Line of the High Priests; Levi
\p
\v 1 Levi'sÂŠ189706 sonsÂŠ189705 were GershonÂŠ189707, KohatÂŠ189708, andÂŠ189709 MerariÂŠ189709.
\p
\v 2 Kohat's sonsÂŠ189714 were Amram, Yitshar, Hevron, and Uzziel.
\p
\v 3 Amram'sÂŠ189723 children were Miryam \add (Miriam)\add*, Aharon \add (Aaron)\add*, and Mosheh \add (Moses)\add*.
\p Aharon's sonsÂŠ189721 were Nadav, Avihu, Eleazar, and Ithamar.
\p
\v 4 Eleazar was the father of Pinehas, \add and\add* Pinehas was the father of Avishua.
\v 5 Avishua was the father of Bukki, and Bukki was the father of Uzzi.
\v 6 Uzzi was the father of Zerahyah, and Zerahyah was the father of Merayot.
\v 7 Merayot fathered Amaryah, and Amaryah fathered Ahituv.
\v 8 Ahituv was the father of Tsadok, and Tsadok was the father of Ahimaats.
\v 9 Ahimaats was the father of Azaryah, andÂŠ189782 Azaryah was the father of Yohanan.
\v 10 Yohanan was the father of Azaryah. Azaryah was a priest in the temple that Shelomoh \add (Solomon)\add* built in Yerushalem.
\v 11 Azaryah was the father of Amaryah, andÂŠ189798 Amaryah was the father of Ahituv.
\v 12 Ahituv was the father of Tsadok, and Tsadok was the father of Shallum.
\v 13 Shallum was the father of Hilkiyah, and Hilkiyah was the father of Azaryah.
\v 14 Azaryah was the father of Serayah, and Serayah was the father of Yehotsadak.
\p
\v 15 Yehotsadak \add âwas included\add* when Yahweh \add âsent\add* Nevuchadnetstsar to take Yehudah (\add âwhich includes\add* Yerushalem) into exile.
\s1 Levi's other descendants
\rem /s1 Other Descendants of Levi; The Levite Clans
\p
\v 16 Levi's sons were Gershon, Kohat, andÂŠ189838 Merari.\x + \xo 6:16-19: \xt Exo 6:16-19.\x*
\v 17 The names of Gershon's sons were Libni and Shimei.
\v 18 Kohat's sons were Amram, Yitshar, Hevron, and Uzziel.
\v 19 Merari's sons were Mahli and Mushi.
\p \add Here's a list of\add* \add âLevi's descendants who became leaders of their clans:\add*
\p
\v 20 Gershon's \add oldest\add* son was Libni, Libni's son was Yahat, \add and\add* Yahat's son was Zimmah.
\v 21 Zimmah's son was Yoah, Yoah's son was Iddo, Iddo's son was Zerah, \add and\add* Zerah's son was Yeaterai.
\p
\v 22 \add Another line of Kohat's descendants started with his son Amminadav.\add* Amminadav's son was Korah. Korah'sÂŠ189946 son was AssirÂŠ189940.
\v 23 Assir's son was Elkanah. Elkanah's son was Evyasaf. Evyasaf's son was Assir.
\v 24 \add Assir's son was Tahat.\add* Tahat's son was Uriel. Uriel's son was Uzziyah. Uzziyah's son was Shaul.
\p
\v 25 Elkanah's sons were Amasai, Ahimot,
\v 26 and a son also named Elkanah. Elkanah's son was Tsofai. Tsofai's son was Nahat.
\v 27 \add Nahat's son was Eliav.\add* Eliav's son was Yeroham. Yeroham's son was Elkanah.
\p
\v 28 Shemuel had sons: his oldest son \add Yoel\add* and his other son Aviyah.
\p
\v 29 Merari'sÂŠ190024 descendants started with Mahli. Mahli's son was Libni. Libni's son was Shimei. Shimei's son was Uzzah.
\v 30 \add Uzzah's son was Shimea.\add* Shimea's son was Haggiyah. Haggiyah's son was Asayah.
\s1 The temple musicians
\rem /s1 The Temple Musicians; Musicians Appointed by David
\rem /s2 The Temple Musicians
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 31 These \add are the men that\add* David put in charge of music in Yahweh's residence, after the \add sacred\add* chest was placed there.
\v 32 They were the ones who had ministered in the sacred tent (\add also called\add* âthe meeting tentâ) with music until Shelomoh \add (Solomon)\add* built the temple in Yerushalem. They performed their duties according to their instructions.
\p
\v 33 \add âHere is a list of the musicians\add* andÂŠ190078 theirÂŠ190078 sons:
\li1 From Kohat's descendants there was Heman, the leader of the singers.
\li1 Heman was Yoel's son.
\li1 Yoel was Shemuel's son.
\li1
\v 34 Samuel was Elkanah's son.
\li1 Elkanah was Yeroham's son.
\li1 Yeroham was Eliel's son.
\li1 Eliel was Toah's son.
\li1
\v 35 Toah was Tsuf's son.
\li1 Tsuf was Elkanah's son.
\li1 Elkanah was Mahat's son.
\li1 Mahat was Amasai's son.
\li1
\v 36 Amasai was Elkanah's son.
\li1 Elkanah was Yoel's son.
\li1 Yoel was Azaryah's son.
\li1 Azaryah was Tsefanyah's son.
\li1
\v 37 Tsefanyah was Tahat's son.
\li1 Tahat was Assir's son.
\li1 Assir was Evyasaf's son.
\li1 Evyasaf was Korah's son.
\li1
\v 38 Korah was Yitshar's son.
\li1 Yitshar was Kohat's son.
\li1 Kohat was Levi's son.
\li1 Levi was the son of \add Yakov (or Jacob, who was later named\add* Yisrael/\add Israel)\add*.
\p
\v 39 Heman's brother Asaf's \add group\add* stood to the right. Asaf was Berekyah's son. Berekyah was Shimea's son.
\v 40 Shimea was Mikael's son. Michael was Baaseyah's son. Baaseyah was Malkiyah's son.
\v 41 Malkiyah was Etni's son. Etni was Zerah's son. Zerah was Adayah's son.
\v 42 Adayah was Etan's son. Etan was Zimmah's son. Zimmah was Shimei's son.
\v 43 Shimei was Yahat's son. Yahat was Gershon's son. Gershon was Levi's son.
\p
\v 44 Heman's brother Merari's \add group\add* stood to the left. Eytan was Kishi's son. Kishi was Abdi's son. Abdi was Malluk's son.
\v 45 Malluk was Hashavyah's son. Hashavyah was Uzziah's son. Uzziah was Hilkiyah's son.
\v 46 Hilkiyah was Amtsi's son. Amtsi was Bani's son. Bani was Shemer's son.
\v 47 Shemer was Mahli's son. Mahli was Mushi's son. Mushi was Merari's son. Merari was Levi's son.
\p
\v 48 Their other Levite cousins were assigned to various ministries serving in God's residence in the sacred tent.
\rem /s1 The Descendants of Aaron; Aaron's Descendants
\v 49 \add âIt was\add* Aharon \add (Aaron)\add* and his sons who \add âoffered\add* the sacrifices on the altar for burnt offerings and on the altar for incense, for all the work of the holiest place and to make atonement for YisraelÂŠ190333, according to everything that God's servant Mosheh \add (Moses)\add* had instructed.
\v 50 These were Aharon's descendants: Aharon's son was Eleazar. Eleazar's son was Pinehas. Pinehas's son was Avishua.
\v 51 Avishua's son was Bukki. Bukki's son was Uzzi. Uzzi's son was Zerahyah.
\v 52 Zerahyah's son was Merayot. Merayot's son was Amaryah. Amaryah's son was Ahituv.
\v 53 Ahituv's son was Tsadok, and Tsadok's son was Ahimaats.
\s1 The Levites' settlements
\rem /s1 Territory for the Levites; Where the Levites Lived; Settlements of the Levites
\p
\v 54 \add âHere is a list of places where Aharon's descendants lived. Kohat's descendants were the first to be allotted property\add*.
\v 55 They were given \add the city of\add* Hevron in Yehudah \add (Judah)\add* and the surrounding pastureland,
\v 56 \add âexcept that\add* Kalev \add (Caleb)\add* received the fields \add farther from\add* the city and the villages \add around\add* the city. (Kalev was Yefunneh's son.)
\v 57 Those descendants of Aharon were given the refuge cities: Hevron, as well as the towns and pastureland \add around\add* Libnah, Yattir, Eshtemoa,
\v 58 Hilez, Devir,
\v 59 Ashan, and Beyt-Shemesh.
\v 60 From the tribe of Benyamin, they received the cities of Geba, Alemet, and Anatot and their pasturelands. Altogether \add those Kohatite\add* clans received thirteen cities,
\v 61 and the remaining Kohatite clans received ten cities from the clans of the tribeÂŠ190537 of Menashsheh.
\p
\v 62 The clans of Gershon's descendants received thirteen cities from the tribes of Yissakar \add (Issachar)\add*, Asher, Naftali, and the part of the tribe of Menashsheh that lived in the Bashan region \add across the Yordan River\add*.
\v 63 The clans of Merari's descendants \add âreceived\add* twelve cities from the tribesÂŠ190585 of Reuven, Gad, and Zevulun.
\v 64 \add âThe Israeli leaders allotted those\add* towns and the nearby pasturelands to the Levites.
\v 65 They also allotted them the cities from the tribesÂŠ190616 of Yehudah, Shimeon, and Benyamin that were listed above.
\v 66 Some of Kohat's descendants received cities from the tribe of Efrayim.
\v 67 They \add also\add* gave them these refuge cities with the surrounding pasturelands: Shekem, Gezer,
\v 68 Yokmeam, Beyt-Horon,
\v 69 Ayyalon, and Gat-Rimmon.
\v 70 Kohats other descendants received the cities of Aner and Bileam and the nearby pastureland from the half-tribe of Menashsheh \add (that lives west of the Yordan River)\add*.
\p
\v 71 Gershom's descendants (part of the tribe of Manasseh \add that lived across the Yordan River\add*) received two cities and pastureland near them: Golan in the Bashan region, and Ashtarot.
\p
\v 72 From the tribe of Yissakar \add (Issachar) they received cities and\add* pastureland near Kedesh, Daverat,
\v 73 Ramot, and Anem.
\v 74 From the tribe of Asher \add they received cities and\add* pastureland near Mashal, Abdon,
\v 75 Hukok, and Rehob.
\p
\v 76 From the tribe of Naftali \add they received cities and\add* pastureland near Kedesh (in the Galilee region), Hammon, and Kiryatayim.
\p
\v 77 Merari's descendants \add received cities and\add* pasturelands from the tribe of Zevulun near Rimmono and Tabor.
\p
\v 78 From the tribe of Reuven across the Yordan River (opposite Yereho), \add they were allotted cities and towns and\add* pastureland near Betser in the wilderness, Yahtsah,
\v 79 Kedemot, and Mefaat.
\p
\v 80 From the tribe of Gad, \add they received cities and\add* pastureland near Ramot in the Gilead region, Mahanayim,
\v 81 Heshbon, and Yazer.
\c 7
\s1 The descendants of Yissakar (Issachar)
\rem /s1 The Descendants of Issachar; Issachar; Descendants of Issachar
\p
\v 1 Yissakar'sÂŠ190649 fourÂŠ190655 sonsÂŠ190648 were TolaÂŠ190650, PuahÂŠ190651, YashubÂŠ190652, and ShimronÂŠ190654.
\v 2 Tola's sonsÂŠ190658 were UzziÂŠ190660, Refayah, YerielÂŠ190662, YahmaiÂŠ190663, IbsamÂŠ190664, and ShemuelÂŠ190665 \add who all became\add* leaders of their clans. \add âThere were strong warriors in the record of Tola's descendants in each generationÂŠ190673\add*. (During the time that DavidÂŠ190676 was Yisrael's king, there were 22,600 such men.)
\p
\v 3 Uzzi'sÂŠ190686 son was Yizrahyah. Yizrahyah's five sons were Mikael, Ovadyah, YoelÂŠ190692, and Yishiyah. They were all \add âleaders of theirÂŠ190696 clans\add*.
\v 4 Along with them according to their \add âfamily records\add*, were 36,000 troopsÂŠ190702 in the army, because theyÂŠ190710 \add âhad numerous\add* wivesÂŠ190711 andÂŠ190698 sonsÂŠ190712.
\v 5 Altogether, Yissakar's clansÂŠ190716 had 87,000 strong warriors listed in their genealogyÂŠ190723.
\s1 Benyamin's descendants
\rem /s1 Descendants of Benjamin; Benjamin; The Descendants of Benjamin and Dan
\p
\v 6 Benyamin'sÂŠ190727 threeÂŠ190731 \add sons\add* were BelaÂŠ190728, BekerÂŠ190729, and YediaelÂŠ190730.
\v 7 Bela'sÂŠ190734 fiveÂŠ190740 sonsÂŠ190733 were Etsbon, UzziÂŠ190736, UzzielÂŠ190737, Yerimot, andÂŠ190733 IriÂŠ190739 who were leaders of their clans. According to their family records, they had 22,034 strong warriors.
\p
\v 8 Beker's sons were ZemirahÂŠ190756, YoashÂŠ190757, EliezerÂŠ190758, Elyehoenai, OmriÂŠ190760, Yeremot, Aviyah, AnatotÂŠ190763, and AlemetÂŠ190764.
\v 9 Altogether, their clans had 20,200 strong warriors listed in their genealogyÂŠ190772.
\p
\v 10 Yediael'sÂŠ190785 son was Bilhan. Bilhan'sÂŠ190786 sons were YeushÂŠ190789, BenyaminÂŠ190791, EhudÂŠ190792, KenaanahÂŠ190793, ZetanÂŠ190794, TarshishÂŠ190795, and AhishaharÂŠ190796.
\v 11 All those descendants of YediaelÂŠ190802 were \add âclan leaders\add* and strong warriors, having 17,200 men ready to go to war.
\p
\v 12 The ShuppitesÂŠ190816 and Huppites were descendants of Ir, \add and\add* the Hushites were descendants of AherÂŠ190822.
\s1 The descendants of Naftali (Naphtali)
\rem /s1 Descendants of Naphtali; The Descendants of Naphtali; Naphtali
\p
\v 13 Naftali'sÂŠ190825 sons were Yahtsiel, GuniÂŠ190827, Yetser, and ShallumÂŠ190829. (\add They were\add* descendants of \add Yakov's slave-wife\add* BilhahÂŠ190831.)
\s1 Menashsheh's descendants
\rem /s1 The Descendants of Manasseh; Manasseh; Descendants of Manasseh
\p
\v 14 MenashshehÂŠ190835 had sonsÂŠ190834 by his \add âSyrianÂŠ190840\add* (Heb. ArameanÂŠ190840) slave-wife. She gave birth to AsrielÂŠ190836, and MakirÂŠ190844 (\add who became\add* the fatherÂŠ190845 of GileadÂŠ190846).
\v 15 Makir \add âmarried\add* a wife from the Huppites and ShuppitesÂŠ190852. (His sister'sÂŠ190854 name was Maakah.) \add âAnother\add* descendant was Tselofehad and he had daughtersÂŠ190861.
\v 16 Makir'sÂŠ190867 wifeÂŠ190865 (\add also calledÂŠ190869\add* Maakah) bore a son and named him PereshÂŠ190871 (and named his brother ShereshÂŠ190874) and his sonsÂŠ190875 were UlamÂŠ190876 and Rakem.
\v 17 Ulam'sÂŠ190880 son was BedanÂŠ190881. Those were the descendantsÂŠ190883 of GileadÂŠ190884 (Makir'sÂŠ190887 son andÂŠ190879 Menashsheh'sÂŠ190890 grandson).
\p
\v 18 \add @Gilead's\add* sisterÂŠ190892 was HammoleketÂŠ190893. She was the mother of IshhodÂŠ190897, Aviezer, andÂŠ190892 MahlahÂŠ190903.
\p
\v 19 \add Another son of Gilead was\add* ShemidaÂŠ190907, whose sonsÂŠ190906 were Ahyan, Shekem, LikhiÂŠ190910, andÂŠ190905 AniamÂŠ190911.
\s1 Efrayim's descendants
\rem /s1 Descendants of Ephraim; The Descendants of Ephraim; Ephraim
\p
\v 20 These are Efrayim'sÂŠ190915 descendants:
\p One son of Efrayim was Shutelah. Shutelah'sÂŠ190916 son was Bered. Bered'sÂŠ190917 son was Tahat. Tahat'sÂŠ190919 son was Eleadah. Eleadah'sÂŠ190921 son \add was also named\add* Tahat.
\v 21 \add @Tahat's\add* son was Zavad. Zavad's son was ShutelahÂŠ190928. Efrayim's other sons, EzerÂŠ190930 andÂŠ190926 EleadÂŠ190931, wentÂŠ190939 to GatÂŠ190935 city to steal some cattle but were killedÂŠ190932 by \add âsome of the natives of that area\add*.
\v 22 Their fatherÂŠ190947 EfrayimÂŠ190946 mournedÂŠ190945 for \add âquite some time\add*, andÂŠ190950 his relativesÂŠ190951 cameÂŠ190950 to comfortÂŠ190952 himÂŠ190952.
\v 23 ThenÂŠ190954 he \add âslept with\add* his wife and she \add âgot pregnantÂŠ190958\add* and \add âgaveÂŠ190959 birthÂŠ190959 to\add* a son. \add @Efrayim\add* \add ânamed him\add* BeriahÂŠ190965 \add (which sounds like the Hebrew word for âtroubleâ)\add*, because \add âof the recent tragedy in their family\add*.
\p
\v 24 Efrayim's daughterÂŠ190971 was Sheerah and she founded three towns: Lower Beyt-Horon, Upper Beyt-Horon, and UzzenÂŠ190984-Sheerah.
\p
\v 25 \add Another son of Efrayim\add* was Refah. Refah's son was Reshef. Reshef'sÂŠ190989 son was Telah. Telah'sÂŠ190990 son was TahanÂŠ190992.
\v 26 \add Tahan's\add* son was Ladan. Ladan's son was Ammihud. Ammihud'sÂŠ190997 son was Elishama.
\v 27 \add Elishama's\add* son was Nun. Nun's son was Yehoshua \add (or Joshua, who led Yisrael's descendants after Mosheh)\add*.
\p
\v 28 \add This is a list of\add* \add âthe cities and areas where Efrayim's descendants lived\add*: Beyt-El and the nearby villages, NaaranÂŠ191014 to the east, GezerÂŠ191016 to the west and the nearby villages, and Shekem and the nearby villages extending \add north\add* as far as AyyahÂŠ191022 and its villages.
\p
\v 29 Along the border of the area where the descendants of MenashshehÂŠ191030 lived were theseÂŠ191041 towns: Beyt-Shan, Taanak, MegiddoÂŠ191037, DorÂŠ191039, andÂŠ191025 all the nearby villages. The people who lived in all those places were descendants of Yakov's son YosefÂŠ191044 \add (Joseph)\add*.
\s1 Asher's descendants
\rem /s1 Asher; The Descendants of Asher
\p
\v 30 Asher'sÂŠ191051 sonsÂŠ191050 were Yimnah, Yishvah, Yishvi, and BeriahÂŠ191055. Their sisterÂŠ191057 was SerahÂŠ191056.
\p
\v 31 Beriah'sÂŠ191060 sonsÂŠ191059 were Hever andÂŠ191062 Malkiel. Malkiel was the fatherÂŠ191064 of Birzayit.
\p
\v 32 Heber was the fatherÂŠ191069 of YafletÂŠ191072, ShomerÂŠ191075, HotamÂŠ191078, andÂŠ191068 theirÂŠ191081 sisterÂŠ191081 ShuaÂŠ191080.
\v 33 Yaflet'sÂŠ191084 sons were Pasak, BimhalÂŠ191086, andÂŠ191083 AshvatÂŠ191087.
\p
\v 34 Shomer's sonsÂŠ191092 were AhiÂŠ191094, RohgahÂŠ191095, Hubbah, andÂŠ191092 AramÂŠ191099.
\p
\v 35 \add Shomer's younger\add* brother was Helem. Helem'sÂŠ191103 sonsÂŠ191101 were Tsofah, Yimna, SheleshÂŠ191107, andÂŠ191101 AmalÂŠ191108.
\p
\v 36 Zofah'sÂŠ191111 sonsÂŠ191110 were SuahÂŠ191112, HarneferÂŠ191113, ShualÂŠ191114, BeriÂŠ191115, YimrahÂŠ191116,
\v 37 Betser, HodÂŠ191119, ShammaÂŠ191120, ShilshahÂŠ191121, Yitran (whose other name was Yeter), and BeeraÂŠ191123.
\p
\v 38 Yeter'sÂŠ191126 sonsÂŠ191125 were YefunnehÂŠ191127, PispahÂŠ191128, andÂŠ191125 AraÂŠ191129.
\v 39 \add Another descendant of Asher was\add* UllaÂŠ191132, whose sonsÂŠ191131 were ArahÂŠ191133, HannielÂŠ191134, andÂŠ191131 Ritsia.
\p
\v 40 All those were Asher'sÂŠ191142 descendantsÂŠ191140, \add âclan leaders\add*, chosenÂŠ191147, very strong, \add âleaders of leaders\add*. And listed in their genealogyÂŠ191152 in the army for war, their numberÂŠ191155, 26,000 men.
\c 8
\s1 Benyamin's descendants
\rem /s1 Descendants of Benjamin; The Genealogy of Saul the Benjamite; The Descendants of Benjamin
\p
\v 1 BenyaminÂŠ191162 had sons: BelaÂŠ191166, AshbelÂŠ191168, AharahÂŠ191170,
\v 2 Nohah, andÂŠ191175 the fifthÂŠ191176, RafaÂŠ191175.
\p
\v 3 Bela'sÂŠ191181 sonsÂŠ191180 were AddarÂŠ191182, GeraÂŠ191183, AbihudÂŠ191184,
\v 4 Avishua, NaamanÂŠ191187, AhoahÂŠ191188,
\v 5 Gera, Shefufan, andÂŠ191190 HuramÂŠ191192.
\p
\v 6 \add One of Gera's sonsÂŠ191195 was\add* EhudÂŠ191196. \add âHis descendants were leaders of their clans who lived\add* in GebaÂŠ191202 \add city\add*, but were taken into exile to ManahatÂŠ191206.
\v 7 Ehud's sons were Naaman, AhijahÂŠ191209, and Gera. Gera \add âwas the one who led them\add* \add when they moved to Manahat\add*. He \add âwas the fatherÂŠ191213 of\add* Uzza and AhihudÂŠ191219.
\p
\v 8 \add Another descendant of Benyamin was\add* ShaharayimÂŠ191221 \add âwho lived\add* in the MoabÂŠ191224 countrysideÂŠ191223. He \add âdivorced\add* his wivesÂŠ191233 HushimÂŠ191229 andÂŠ191230 BaaraÂŠ191232
\v 9 andÂŠ191235 fatheredÂŠ191235 \add sons\add* with his wife HodeshÂŠ191238: YobabÂŠ191242, TsivyaÂŠ191245, MeshaÂŠ191248, MalkamÂŠ191251,
\v 10 Yeuts, Sakeya, andÂŠ191253 MirmahÂŠ191261. They all became leaders of their clans.
\v 11 (He had fatheredÂŠ191268 Avituv andÂŠ191272 ElpaalÂŠ191274 by Hushim.)
\p
\v 12 Elpaal'sÂŠ191277 sonsÂŠ191276 were EberÂŠ191278, MishamÂŠ191279, ShemedÂŠ191280 (who builtÂŠ191282 OnoÂŠ191285 \add city\add*, plus LodÂŠ191288 andÂŠ191276 itsÂŠ191289 townsÂŠ191289),
\s2 Benyamin's descendants in Gat and Ayyalon
\rem /s1 The Benjaminites in Gath and Aijalon
\p
\v 13 plus Beriah andÂŠ191292 ShemaÂŠ191292 who were leaders of their clans who lived in Ayyalon \add city\add*. They forced the people who lived in GatÂŠ191303 city to flee.
\v 14-16 Beriah's sons were Ahyo, ShashakÂŠ191306, Yeremot, Zevadyah, Arad, Eder, Mikael, Yishpah, andÂŠ191307 Yoha.
\s2 Benyamin's descendants in Yerushalem
\rem /s1 The Benjaminites in Jerusalem
\p
\v 17-18 \add Other\add* descendants of Elpaal were Zevadyah, MeshullamÂŠ191320, HizkiÂŠ191321, HeberÂŠ191322, Yishmerai, Yizliah, andÂŠ191319 Yovav.
\p
\v 19-21 \add Another descendant of Benyamin was Shimei.\add* Shimei's descendants \add âincluded\add* Yakim, ZikriÂŠ191331, Zavdi, Elienai, Tsilletai, Eliel, Adayah, Berayah, andÂŠ191330 Shimrat.
\p
\v 22-25 Shashak's sons were YishpanÂŠ191344, EberÂŠ191345, ElielÂŠ191346, Avdon, Zikri, Hanan, Hananyah, Elam, Antotiyah, Iphdeiah, andÂŠ191344 Penuel.
\p
\v 26-27 \add Another descendant of Benyamin was\add* Yeroham, whose sons were ShamsheraiÂŠ191362, SheharyahÂŠ191363, Atalyah, Yaareshyah, Eliyah, andÂŠ191362 Zikri.
\p
\v 28 \add @All those descendants of Elpaal (Shaharayim's son)\add* were \add âleaders of their clans accordingÂŠ191375 to their genealogies\add*. They \add all\add* lived in YerushalemÂŠ191379.
\s2 Benyamin's descendants in Gibeon
\rem /s1 The Family of Saul; The Benjaminites in Gibeon and Jerusalem
\p
\v 29 \add Another descendant of Benyamin was Yeiel\add*âhe \add âwas a founder of\add* GibeonÂŠ191382 \add city\add*. His wife was Maakah.
\v 30 His sons, \add starting with\add* the eldest, were Avdon, TsurÂŠ191393, KishÂŠ191394, BaalÂŠ191395, Nadav,
\v 31 Gedor, Ahyo, andÂŠ191398 ZekerÂŠ191400.
\v 32 Miklot \add (another of Yeiel's sons)\add* was the fatherÂŠ191403 of Shimeah. All those descendants of Yeiel also lived in YerushalemÂŠ191413 near their relativesÂŠ191411.
\s1 The descendants of King Shaul (Saul)
\rem /s1 The Family of King Saul
\p
\v 33 NerÂŠ191419 was the father of Kish. Kish was the father of \add King\add* Shaul. Shaul was the father of Yonatan \add (Jonathan)\add*, MalkiÂŠ191436-ShuaÂŠ191438, Avinadav, and Esh-Baal.
\v 34 Yonatan's son was Meriv-Baal. Meriv-Baal was the fatherÂŠ191453 of Mikah.
\p
\v 35 Mikah'sÂŠ191460 sonsÂŠ191459 were PithonÂŠ191461, MelekÂŠ191462, TareaÂŠ191463, and AhazÂŠ191464.
\v 36 Ahaz was the father of Yehoaddah. Yehoaddah was the father of AlemetÂŠ191475, AzmavetÂŠ191478, andÂŠ191466 Zimri. Zimri was the father of Motsa.
\v 37 Motsa was the fatherÂŠ191489 of Binea. Rafah was Binea'sÂŠ191492 son. Eleasah was Raphah's son. Atsel was Eleasah'sÂŠ191495 son.
\p
\v 38 Atsel had \add âa total of\add* six sons named AzrikamÂŠ191505, Bokeru, YishmaelÂŠ191508, ShearyahÂŠ191509, Ovadyah, andÂŠ191500 HananÂŠ191511.
\v 39 Atsel had a brother, Eshek. Eshek'sÂŠ191519 oldest son was UlamÂŠ191521. His other sonsÂŠ191518 were YeushÂŠ191523 andÂŠ191525 ElifeletÂŠ191525.
\p
\v 40 Ulam'sÂŠ191531 sons were powerful warriors who were also archers. Altogether they had 150 sons andÂŠ191528 grandsons.
\p All those were Benyamin'sÂŠ191548 descendants.
\c 9
\s1 Those who returned from captivity
\rem /s1 The restored community; The People Who Returned from Captivity
\p
\v 1 \add âSo\add* all Yisrael \add âwere listed in genealogy\add*, and yes, they're writtenÂŠ191556 on the scrollÂŠ191559 of Yisrael's kingsÂŠ191560.
\rem /s1 The Returning Exiles; The People in Jerusalem
\p Then Yehudah \add (Judah)\add* was takenÂŠ191563 into exileÂŠ191563 to BabylonÂŠ191564 because of theirÂŠ191565 unfaithfulnessÂŠ191565.
\v 2 The firstÂŠ191569 \add âto return and resettle their land and\add* their cities were \add some\add* priestsÂŠ191574, LevitesÂŠ191575, templeÂŠ191576 servantsÂŠ191576, and \add other\add* Israelis.\x + \xo 9:2-3: \xt Ezr 2:27; Neh 7:73.\x*
\rem /s1 Inhabitants of Jerusalem after the Exile
\v 3 \add Some from the tribes of\add* YehudahÂŠ191583, BenyaminÂŠ191587, EfrayimÂŠ191591, and MenashshehÂŠ191592 \add also returned and\add* lived in Yerushalem, \add including the following:\add*
\p
\v 4 Utai son of Ammihud (Ammihud was Omri'sÂŠ191600 son, Omri was Imri'sÂŠ191603 son, Imri was Bani's son, Bani was a descendantÂŠ191609 of Perets, Perets was Yehudah'sÂŠ191614 son),
\v 5 Asayah andÂŠ191621 his sonsÂŠ191621 (descendants of ShilonâAsayah was the oldest),
\v 6 YeuelÂŠ191628 andÂŠ191623 other relativesÂŠ191629 from Zerah'sÂŠ191627 clan (which included 690 people).
\p
\v 7 From Benyamin' descendantsÂŠ191637, SalluÂŠ191639 (Meshullam'sÂŠ191642 son, Meshullam was Hodavyah'sÂŠ191645 son, Hodavyah was Hassenuah'sÂŠ191648 son),
\v 8 Ibneyah (Yeroham'sÂŠ191653 son), ElahÂŠ191654 (Uzzi'sÂŠ191657 son, Uzzi was Mikri'sÂŠ191660 son), andÂŠ191650 MeshullamÂŠ191661 (Shefatyah's son, Shefatyah was Reuel'sÂŠ191667 son, Reuel was Yivniyah's son).
\p
\v 9 In all, there were 956 of Benyamin's descendants living in Yerushalem. All those \add above\add* were leaders of their clans.
\rem /s1 The Returning Priests; Priestly Families; The Priests Who Lived in Jerusalem
\p
\v 10 Some of the priestsÂŠ191690 \add who returned to Yehudah\add* were: YedayahÂŠ191691, Yehoyariv, Yakin,
\v 11 Azaryah, the leading official at the temple (Azaryah was Hilkiyah's son, Hilkiyah was Meshullam'sÂŠ191701 son, Meshullam was Tsadok'sÂŠ191704 son, Tsadok was Merayot's son, Merayot was Ahituv's son),
\v 12 AdayahÂŠ191716 (Yeroham'sÂŠ191719 son, Yeroham was Pashhur'sÂŠ191722 son, Pashhur was Malkiyah'sÂŠ191725 son), and MaasaiÂŠ191726 (Adiel'sÂŠ191729 son, Adiel was Yahzerah'sÂŠ191732 son, Yahzerah was Meshullam'sÂŠ191735 son, Meshullam was Meshillemit'sÂŠ191738 son, Meshillemit was Immer'sÂŠ191741 son).
\p
\v 13 Altogether there were 1,760 \add priests who returned to Yehudah\add*. \add âThey were leaders of their clans, and they all were capable and responsible\add* to workÂŠ191754 in God's residence.
\s1 Levites who returned
\rem /s1 The Returning Levites; Levitical Families; The Levites Who Lived in Jerusalem
\p
\v 14 From Levi's descendants \add who returned to Yehudah there were\add*: ShemayahÂŠ191762 (Hasshuv's son, Hasshuv was Azrikam'sÂŠ191768 son, Azrikam was Hashavyah's son, Hashavyah was a descendant of \add Levi's youngest son\add* MerariÂŠ191775),
\rem /s1 The Temple Guards Who Lived in Jerusalem
\v 15 Bakbakkar, HereshÂŠ191778, GalalÂŠ191779, MattanyahÂŠ191780 (Mika's son, Mika was Zikri'sÂŠ191786 son, Zikri was Asaf'sÂŠ191789 son),
\v 16 Ovadyah (Shemayah'sÂŠ191794 son, Shemayah was Galal'sÂŠ191797 son, Galal was Yedutun's son), andÂŠ191791 Berekyah who lived in one of the villagesÂŠ191809 where the Netofat people lived (Berekyah was Asa'sÂŠ191804 son, Asa was Elkanah'sÂŠ191807 son).
\p
\v 17 From Levi's descendants who returned to Yehudah who guarded the temple gates there was Shallum, Akkuv, TalmonÂŠ191815, AhimanÂŠ191816, andÂŠ191812 some of their relativesÂŠ191817. Shallum was their leader.
\v 18 Those descendentsÂŠ191830 of LeviÂŠ191831 were gatekeepersÂŠ191828 at the King's Gate on the east \add âeven at the present time\add*.
\p
\v 19 Shallum was Kore'sÂŠ191836 son, Kore was Evyasaph's son, and Evyasaph was Korah's son. Shallum and his relativesÂŠ191843 from his clan (Korah's descendants), had the duty of being gatekeepers, responsible to guard the entrancesÂŠ191860 to Yahweh's temple as theirÂŠ191854 ancestorsÂŠ191854 had done.
\v 20 \add âPreviously\add* Pinehas (Eleazar'sÂŠ191865 son) \add âhad supervised\add* the gatekeepers. YahwehÂŠ191870 was with \add @Pinehas\add*.
\p
\v 21 Zekaryah (Meshelemyah'sÂŠ191876 son) was gatekeeperÂŠ191877 of the entranceÂŠ191878 to the assembly tent.
\v 22 \add âAltogether, there were 212 men chosenÂŠ191883 to guard the gates\add*. \add âThe records of the clans in their villagesÂŠ191890 listed their names\add*. \add King\add* DavidÂŠ191894 and \add âthe prophet\add* Shemuel \add (SamuelÂŠ191895)\add* \add âappointedÂŠ191893 them because theyÂŠ191889 were dependable\add*.
\v 23 They andÂŠ191899 theirÂŠ191900 sons \add watched\add* over the gatesÂŠ191903 of Yahweh's house, i.e., the \add âsacred\add* tent, as guardsÂŠ191910.
\v 24 There were gatekeepersÂŠ191915 on each of the \add temple's\add* fourÂŠ191912 sidesÂŠ191913: east, west, northÂŠ191918, andÂŠ191919 southÂŠ191919.
\v 25 Their relativesÂŠ191921 in their villagesÂŠ191922 would come in from time to time \add to relieve them\add* for sevenÂŠ191924 daysÂŠ191925
\v 26 because the fourÂŠ191937 leaders of the gatekeepersÂŠ191939 were LevitesÂŠ191941, and they were \add also\add* \add âtrustedÂŠ191935 to supervise\add* the chambersÂŠ191945 and the treasuriesÂŠ191947 in God'sÂŠ191949 residence.
\v 27 TheyÂŠ191954 would \add âspend the nightÂŠ191955\add* aroundÂŠ191951 the \add âtemple\add* while they were in charge, andÂŠ191951 \add âwould open it with the key each\add* morning.
\rem /s1 The Other Levites
\p
\v 28 Some of them \add âmonitored the utensils used in the activities\add*âcounting them as they broughtÂŠ191975 them out andÂŠ191976 \add âwhen they put them away\add* \add again\add*.
\v 29 \add âOthers\add* took care of the containers and utensils used in the sanctuaryÂŠ191988, along with the fine flourÂŠ191991, the wine and oil, and the frankincense and spicesÂŠ191995.
\v 30 Some of the priestsÂŠ192000 mixedÂŠ192001 \add the fragrances andÂŠ191997\add* spicesÂŠ192003.
\p
\v 31 There was a LeviteÂŠ192008 \add named\add* MattithiahÂŠ192005 (the oldest son of ShallumÂŠ192011, who was a descendant of Korah) whose official duty \add âwas supervising the baking of the flat breads\add*.
\v 32 Some of Kohat's descendants preparedÂŠ192029 the rows of breadÂŠ192027 to \add laid out on the sacred table\add* every rest day.
\p
\v 33 Some of Levi's descendants were \add temple musicians and\add* singersÂŠ192035. The leaders of those families stayed in the temple accommodations. They \add âdidn't have other duties\add* because theyÂŠ192046 \add were expected to\add* serve dayÂŠ192044 and nightÂŠ192045.
\v 34 Those were the headsÂŠ192050 of the LeviteÂŠ192052 \add âfamiliesÂŠ192051\add* accordingÂŠ192053 to theirÂŠ192053 generationsÂŠ192053 \add and\add* theyÂŠ192056 lived in YerushalemÂŠ192057.
\s1 King Shaul's ancestors and descendants
\rem /s1 The Ancestors and Descendants of King Saul; The Genealogy of Saul; King Saul's Family Tree; The Family of King Saul
\r (1 Chr. 8:29-38)
\p
\v 35 \add Another descendant of Benyamin was\add* YeielÂŠ192065. He was \add âa founder\add* of GibeonÂŠ192060 \add city\add* and lived there. His wife was Maakah.
\v 36 His oldest son was Avdon, andÂŠ192071 his other sons were TsurÂŠ192074, KishÂŠ192075, BaalÂŠ192076, NerÂŠ192077, Nadav,
\v 37 Gedor, Ahyo, Zekaryah, andÂŠ192080 MiklotÂŠ192083.
\v 38 Miklot was the fatherÂŠ192086 of Shimeam. They also lived \add ânear\add* their relatives in YerushalemÂŠ192096.
\p
\v 39 NerÂŠ192102 was the father of Kish. Kish was the father of \add King\add* Shaul \add (SaulÂŠ192111)\add*. Shaul was the father of Yonatan \add (Jonathan)\add*, MalkiÂŠ192119-ShuaÂŠ192121, Avinadav, and Esh-Baal.
\v 40 Yonatan's son was Meriv-Baal. Meriv-Baal was the fatherÂŠ192137 of Mikah.
\v 41 Mikah'sÂŠ192143 sonsÂŠ192142 were PitonÂŠ192144, MelekÂŠ192145, andÂŠ192142 TahreaÂŠ192146.
\v 42 Ahaz was the father of Yarah. Yarah was the father of AlemetÂŠ192157, AzmavetÂŠ192160, andÂŠ192148 Zimri. Zimri was the father of Motsa.
\v 43 Moza was the fatherÂŠ192171 of Binea. Refayah was Binea'sÂŠ192174 son. Eleasah was Refayah's son. Atsel was Eleasah'sÂŠ192177 son.
\p
\v 44 Atsel had six sons named AzrikamÂŠ192187, Bokeru, YishmaelÂŠ192190, ShearyahÂŠ192191, Ovadyah, andÂŠ192182 HananÂŠ192193.
\c 10
