\v 1 \add âSome time later\add*, the Ammonite King NahashÂŠ196098 died and his son \add Hanun\add* \add âbecameÂŠ196103 their king\add*
\v 2 andÂŠ196107 David said, âI'll show loyal commitment to Nahash'sÂŠ196118 son Hanun, because his father \add âwas good to me\add*.â \add âSoÂŠ196107\add* David sent messengersÂŠ196127 to comfort him concerning his father's \add death\add*. \add âHowever,\add* when David'sÂŠ196108 servantsÂŠ196133 \add âentered Ammonite territory\add* to comfort Hanun,
\v 3 the Ammonite leadersÂŠ196147 \add âasked their new king\add*, â\add âDo you think that\add* David'sÂŠ196153 \add really\add* sending comfortersÂŠ196162 to honourÂŠ196152 yourÂŠ196157 father? \add âWouldn't it be more likely that he sentÂŠ196160 his servantsÂŠ196170 to explore andÂŠ196146 spy out the land in order to overthrowÂŠ196166 you\add*?â
\v 4 \add âSo\add* \add King\add* HanunÂŠ196175 tookÂŠ196174 David'sÂŠ196179 servantsÂŠ196178, and \add had their beards\add* shavedÂŠ196180 off, plus he cut \add âoff the bottom half of their robes to expose their\add* buttocks, and then he sentÂŠ196189 them \add âhome\add*.
\v 5 \add âSome people quickly informed DavidÂŠ196193 what had happened\add*, so he sent \add messengers\add* to meet the men (because they were very much humiliatedÂŠ196203) andÂŠ196191 to tell them, âStay \add there\add* in Yeriho \add (Jericho)\add* untilÂŠ196209 your beardsÂŠ196213 grow \add out\add*, thenÂŠ196191 returnÂŠ196214 \add here\add*.â
\p
\v 6 \add âBy thenÂŠ196216\add*, the Ammonites \add ârealised that they had greatly insulted\add* \add King\add* DavidÂŠ196223, \add âso\add* \add King\add* HanunÂŠ196225 and the Ammonites sentÂŠ196224 thirty tonnes of silverÂŠ196231 to hire chariotsÂŠ196243 and horsemenÂŠ196244 from Aram-Naharayim, Aram-Maakah, and Tsovah.
\v 7 They hiredÂŠ196246 32,000 chariotsÂŠ196251, \add âas well as\add* the kingÂŠ196254 of Maakah and his army. They \add all\add* came and \add âset up their camps near\add* Meydeva, \add âplus they were joined by\add* the Ammonites \add themselves\add* coming out of their citiesÂŠ196266 ready for battleÂŠ196268.
\p
\v 8 \add âWhen\add* DavidÂŠ196272 heard \add about that\add*, he sentÂŠ196273 Yoav \add âwith the entireÂŠ196278\add* army.
\v 9 ThenÂŠ196283 the AmmonitesÂŠ196285 marched out andÂŠ196283 deployed ready for battleÂŠ196287 at the entranceÂŠ196288 to their cityÂŠ196289, while kingsÂŠ196290 who had comeÂŠ196293 were over in the countrysideÂŠ196295 \add with their men\add*.
\p
\v 10 Yoav \add quickly\add* realised that \add âhe'd have to fight on two fronts, so\add* he choseÂŠ196308 Yisrael's best warriors andÂŠ196297 set them out to faceÂŠ196302 the ArameansÂŠ196315 \add (SyriansÂŠ196315)\add*,
\v 11 while he placed the remaining men (under the control of his \add older brother\add* Avshai) out againstÂŠ196325 the Ammonites.
\v 12 Yoav told them, âIf the ArameansÂŠ196334 are too strong for me, then you \add âcan come to rescue me\add*. \add âButÂŠ196329\add* if the Ammonites \add âstart to gain on you\add*, then I'll \add come to\add* rescue you.
\v 13 We must be strongÂŠ196347 and fight hard to defend our peopleÂŠ196351 and our citiesÂŠ196353 \add âthat belong to\add* our godÂŠ196354. YahwehÂŠ196355 will do \add âwhat he considers to be\add* goodÂŠ196356.â
\p
\v 14 \add âSoÂŠ196360\add* Yoav \add âadvanced hisÂŠ196370 troops to attack the Arameans, but the Arameans fled away from them\add*.
\v 15 \add âWhen\add* the Ammonites sawÂŠ196374 that the ArameansÂŠ196378 had fled, \add âthey also fled from Avshai andÂŠ196372 withdrew into\add* the cityÂŠ196387, \add âso\add* Yoav wentÂŠ196386 back to YerushalemÂŠ196390.
\p
\v 16 \add âWhen the Arameans\add* sawÂŠ196393 thatÂŠ196405 they were defeatedÂŠ196396 \add âby\add* YisraelÂŠ196398, they sentÂŠ196399 messengersÂŠ196400 to bring \add âmore Arameans from across the Euphrates riverÂŠ196407, led by\add* Shofak, the commanderÂŠ196409 of Hadadezer'sÂŠ196412 army.
\v 17 \add âWhen\add* that was reported to DavidÂŠ196416, he gatheredÂŠ196417 all YisraelÂŠ196422 andÂŠ196415 crossed the YordanÂŠ196424. They positioned themselves against the ArameansÂŠ196432 who thenÂŠ196415 foughtÂŠ196434 against them.
\v 18 \add âButÂŠ196437 the ArameansÂŠ196438 fled away from the Israelis\add*, and DavidÂŠ196442 killed sevenÂŠ196444 thousand chariotÂŠ196446 \add drivers\add* and fortyÂŠ196447 thousand men on footÂŠ196450, as well as killing Shofak their army commanderÂŠ196453.
\v 19 When Hadadezer'sÂŠ196460 servantsÂŠ196459 sawÂŠ196458 that \add âYisraelÂŠ196464 had defeatedÂŠ196462 them\add*, they made peaceÂŠ196465 with DavidÂŠ196468 andÂŠ196458 \add âbecameÂŠ196469 his subjectsÂŠ196469, so\add* AramÂŠ196473 \add (SyriaÂŠ196473)\add* wasn't willingÂŠ196472 to helpÂŠ196474 the Ammonites \add militarily\add* any more.
\c 20
